      <h2>The basics: premium kibble vs BARF</h2>
      <p>There is no single "best" diet — there is the one that suits your dog, your lifestyle, and your budget. What we can say with certainty: <strong>ingredient quality comes before everything else</strong>. A Nordic dog fed on budget supermarket kibble will pay the price in coat quality, energy, and lifespan.</p>

      <h3>Kibble — our recommendation</h3>
      <p>For our breeds, we recommend grain-free kibble or kibble with ancestral grains (millet, quinoa), with a real meat content above 60%. Nordic breeds have a high metabolism and a digestive system sensitive to refined grains.</p>
      <div class="tip-box"><strong>Vet-approved brands:</strong> Orijen, Acana, Taste of the Wild, Canagan, Schesir Air Dry. Avoid supermarket brands — the ingredient list tells the whole story at a glance.</div>

      <h3>BARF — raw feeding</h3>
      <p>BARF (Biologically Appropriate Raw Food) means feeding your dog raw meat, meaty bones, offal, and vegetables. It is the diet closest to an animal's natural needs. Benefits: glossy coat, less waste, clean teeth. Constraints: preparation time, storage, strict nutritional balance required.</p>
      <p>If you want to switch to BARF, do it gradually over 3 weeks — ideally with guidance from a veterinary nutritionist.</p>

